attributes.description: COLDCOPY is a ClickFix lure which masquerades as a custom CAPTCHA. COLDCOPY prompts the target to download and execute a DLL using rundll32, while trying to disguise itself as a CAPTCHA by including text to verify that the user is not a robot.
attributes.name: COLDCOPY

attributes.description: UNC4057 is an espionage cluster that is engaged in highly targeted credential harvesting operations in support of Russian national interests. Since the Russian re-invasion of Ukraine in February 2022, UNC4057 has targeted a range of organizations involved in various forms of military and humanitarian support to Ukraine as well as security-related organizations in NATO countries. Operations are often targeted at the personal mailboxes of its victims, pointing to the group's likely interest in collecting both personal information and intelligence information. Notably, public reporting has also tied the group to hack-and-leak operations, indicating a possible growing mandate for cyber-enabled operations as well.
attributes.name: UNC4057

value.title: Shadow Copies Deletion Using Operating Systems Utilities
value.author: Florian Roth (Nextron Systems), Michael Haag, Teymur Kheirkhabarov, Daniil Yugoslavskiy, oscd.community, Andreas Hunkeler (@Karneades)
value.description: Shadow Copies deletion using operating systems utilities

value.title: Suspicious Volume Shadow Copy VSS_PS.dll Load
value.author: Markus Neis, @markus_neis
value.description:
Detects the image load of vss_ps.dll by uncommon executables. This DLL is used by the Volume Shadow Copy Service (VSS) to manage shadow copies of files and volumes.
It is often abused by attackers to delete or manipulate shadow copies, which can hinder forensic investigations and data recovery efforts.
The fact that it is loaded by processes that are not typically associated with VSS operations can indicate suspicious activity.

value.title: Uncommon File Created In Office Startup Folder
value.author: frack113, Nasreddine Bencherchali (Nextron Systems)
value.description: Detects the creation of a file with an uncommon extension in an Office application startup folder

value.title: Base64 Encoded PowerShell Command Detected
value.author: Florian Roth (Nextron Systems)
value.description: Detects usage of the "FromBase64String" function in the commandline which is used to decode a base64 encoded string

value.title: Suspicious Startup Folder Persistence
value.author: Nasreddine Bencherchali (Nextron Systems), Swachchhanda Shrawan Poudel (Nextron Systems)
value.description:
Detects the creation of potentially malicious script and executable files in Windows startup folders, which is a common persistence technique used by threat actors.
These files (.ps1, .vbs, .js, .bat, etc.) are automatically executed when a user logs in, making the Startup folder an attractive target for attackers.
This technique is frequently observed in malvertising campaigns and malware distribution where attackers attempt to maintain long-term access to compromised systems.

value.title: Suspicious PowerShell Get Current User
value.author: frack113
value.description: Detects the use of PowerShell to identify the current logged user.

value.title: Remotely Hosted HTA File Executed Via Mshta.EXE
value.author: Nasreddine Bencherchali (Nextron Systems)
value.description: Detects execution of the "mshta" utility with an argument containing the "http" keyword, which could indicate that an attacker is executing a remotely hosted malicious hta file

value.title: PowerShell Script Run in AppData
value.author: Florian Roth (Nextron Systems), Jonhnathan Ribeiro, oscd.community
value.description: Detects a suspicious command line execution that invokes PowerShell with reference to an AppData folder

value.title: Suspicious File Access to Browser Credential Storage
value.author: frack113, X__Junior (Nextron Systems), Swachchhanda Shrawan Poudel (Nextron Systems), Parth-FourCore
value.description:
Detects file access to browser credential storage paths by non-browser processes, which may indicate credential access attempts.
Adversaries may attempt to access browser credential storage to extract sensitive information such as usernames and passwords or cookies.
This behavior is often commonly observed in credential stealing malware.

value.title: Credential Manager Access By Uncommon Applications
value.author: Nasreddine Bencherchali (Nextron Systems)
value.description:
Detects suspicious processes based on name and location that access the windows credential manager and vault.
Which can be a sign of credential stealing. Example case would be usage of mimikatz "dpapi::cred" function

value.title: PowerShell Base64 Encoded FromBase64String Cmdlet
value.author: Florian Roth (Nextron Systems)
value.description: Detects usage of a base64 encoded "FromBase64String" cmdlet in a process command line

value.title: Suspicious MSHTA Child Process
value.author: Michael Haag
value.description: Detects a suspicious process spawning from an "mshta.exe" process, which could be indicative of a malicious HTA script execution

value.title: Suspicious PowerShell Parent Process
value.author: Teymur Kheirkhabarov, Harish Segar
value.description: Detects a suspicious or uncommon parent processes of PowerShell

value.title: Access To Windows DPAPI Master Keys By Uncommon Applications
value.author: Nasreddine Bencherchali (Nextron Systems)
value.description:
Detects file access requests to the the Windows Data Protection API Master keys by an uncommon application.
This can be a sign of credential stealing. Example case would be usage of mimikatz "dpapi::masterkey" function

value.title: Outbound Network Connection Initiated By Script Interpreter
value.author: frack113, Florian Roth (Nextron Systems)
value.description: Detects a script interpreter wscript/cscript opening a network connection to a non-local network. Adversaries may use script to download malicious payloads.

value.title: Potentially Suspicious Rundll32 Activity
value.author: juju4, Jonhnathan Ribeiro, oscd.community, Nasreddine Bencherchali (Nextron Systems)
value.description: Detects suspicious execution of rundll32, with specific calls to some DLLs with known LOLBIN functionalities

value.title: DLL Search Order Hijackig Via Additional Space in Path
value.author: frack113, Nasreddine Bencherchali (Nextron Systems)
value.description:
Detects when an attacker create a similar folder structure to windows system folders such as (Windows, Program Files...)
but with a space in order to trick DLL load search order and perform a "DLL Search Order Hijacking" attack

value.title: RegAsm.EXE Execution Without CommandLine Flags or Files
value.author: frack113
value.description:
Detects the execution of "RegAsm.exe" without a commandline flag or file, which might indicate potential process injection activity.
Usually "RegAsm.exe" should point to a dedicated DLL file or call the help with the "/?" flag.

value.title: Suspicious Invoke-WebRequest Execution
value.author: Nasreddine Bencherchali (Nextron Systems)
value.description: Detects a suspicious call to Invoke-WebRequest cmdlet where the and output is located in a suspicious location

value.title: Suspicious Msbuild Execution By Uncommon Parent Process
value.author: frack113
value.description: Detects suspicious execution of 'Msbuild.exe' by a uncommon parent process

value.title: Suspicious Non-Browser Network Communication With Telegram API
value.author: Nasreddine Bencherchali (Nextron Systems)
value.description: Detects an a non-browser process interacting with the Telegram API which could indicate use of a covert C2

value.title: Powershell Token Obfuscation - Powershell
value.author: frack113
value.description: Detects TOKEN OBFUSCATION technique from Invoke-Obfuscation

value.title: Telegram Bot API Request
value.author: Florian Roth (Nextron Systems)
value.description: Detects suspicious DNS queries to api.telegram.org used by Telegram Bots of any kind

value.title: Suspicious Execution of Systeminfo
value.author: frack113
value.description: Detects usage of the "systeminfo" command to retrieve information

value.title: Suspicious Process Discovery With Get-Process
value.author: frack113
value.description: Get the processes that are running on the local computer.

value.title: Suspicious PowerShell Invocations - Specific - ProcessCreation
value.author: Nasreddine Bencherchali (Nextron Systems)
value.description: Detects suspicious PowerShell invocation command parameters

value.title: Windows Shell/Scripting Application File Write to Suspicious Folder
value.author: Florian Roth (Nextron Systems)
value.description: Detects Windows shells and scripting applications that write files to suspicious folders

value.title: Suspicious Volume Shadow Copy Vssapi.dll Load
value.author: frack113
value.description: Detects the image load of VSS DLL by uncommon executables

value.title: Suspicious FromBase64String Usage On Gzip Archive - Ps Script
value.author: frack113
value.description: Detects attempts of decoding a base64 Gzip archive in a PowerShell script. This technique is often used as a method to load malicious content into memory afterward.

value.title: DriverQuery.EXE Execution
value.author: Nasreddine Bencherchali (Nextron Systems)
value.description: Detect usage of the "driverquery" utility. Which can be used to perform reconnaissance on installed drivers

value.title: Remote Access Tool Services Have Been Installed - Security
value.author: Connor Martin, Nasreddine Bencherchali (Nextron Systems)
value.description: Detects service installation of different remote access tools software. These software are often abused by threat actors to perform

value.title: MSHTA Execution with Suspicious File Extensions
value.author: Diego Perez (@darkquassar), Markus Neis, Swisscom (Improve Rule), Swachchhanda Shrawan Poudel (Nextron Systems)
value.description:
Detects execution of mshta.exe with file types that looks like they do not typically represent HTA (HTML Application) content,
such as .png, .jpg, .zip, .pdf, and others, which are often polyglots. MSHTA is a legitimate Windows utility for executing HTML Applications
containing VBScript or JScript. Threat actors often abuse this lolbin utility to download and
execute malicious scripts disguised as benign files or hosted under misleading extensions to evade detection.

value.title: Set Suspicious Files as System Files Using Attrib.EXE
value.author: Nasreddine Bencherchali (Nextron Systems)
value.description: Detects the usage of attrib with the "+s" option to set scripts or executables located in suspicious locations as system files to hide them from users and make them unable to be deleted with simple rights. The rule limits the search to specific extensions and directories to avoid FPs

value.title: DNS Server Discovery Via LDAP Query
value.author: frack113
value.description: Detects DNS server discovery via LDAP query requests from uncommon applications

value.title: DarkGate - Autoit3.EXE Execution Parameters
value.author: Micah Babinski
value.description:
Detects execution of the legitimate Autoit3 utility from a suspicious parent process. AutoIt3.exe is used within
the DarkGate infection chain to execute shellcode that performs process injection and connects to the DarkGate
command-and-control server.

value.title: Search for Antivirus process
value.author: Joe Security
value.description: Search for Antivirus process

value.title: Suspicious Execution of Hostname
value.author: frack113
value.description: Use of hostname to get information

value.title: Silenttrinity Stager Msbuild Activity
value.author: Kiran kumar s, oscd.community
value.description: Detects a possible remote connections to Silenttrinity c2

value.title: Renamed AutoIt Execution
value.author: Florian Roth (Nextron Systems)
value.description:
Detects the execution of a renamed AutoIt2.exe or AutoIt3.exe.
AutoIt is a scripting language and automation tool for Windows systems. While primarily used for legitimate automation tasks, it can be misused in cyber attacks.
Attackers can leverage AutoIt to create and distribute malware, including keyloggers, spyware, and botnets. A renamed AutoIt executable is particularly suspicious.

value.title: Browser Started with Remote Debugging
value.author: pH-T (Nextron Systems), Nasreddine Bencherchali (Nextron Systems)
value.description: Detects browsers starting with the remote debugging flags. Which is a technique often used to perform browser injection attacks

value.title: Windows Defender Service Disabled - Registry
value.author: Ján Trenčanský, frack113, AlertIQ, Nasreddine Bencherchali
value.description: Detects when an attacker or tool disables the  Windows Defender service (WinDefend) via the registry

value.title: Scheduled temp file as task from temp location
value.author: Joe Security
value.description: Scheduled temp file as task from temp location

value.title: Suspicious PowerShell Parameter Substring
value.author: Florian Roth (Nextron Systems), Daniel Bohannon (idea), Roberto Rodriguez (Fix)
value.description: Detects suspicious PowerShell invocation with a parameter substring

value.title: Non Interactive PowerShell Process Spawned
value.author: Roberto Rodriguez @Cyb3rWard0g (rule), oscd.community (improvements)
value.description: Detects non-interactive PowerShell activity by looking at the "powershell" process with a non-user GUI process such as "explorer.exe" as a parent.

value.title: Suspicious DNS Query for IP Lookup Service APIs
value.author: Brandon George (blog post), Thomas Patzke
value.description: Detects DNS queries for IP lookup services such as "api.ipify.org" originating from a non browser process.

value.title: Suspicious Network Connection to IP Lookup Service APIs
value.author: Janantha Marasinghe, Nasreddine Bencherchali (Nextron Systems)
value.description: Detects external IP address lookups by non-browser processes via services such as "api.ipify.org". This could be indicative of potential post compromise internet test activity.

value.title: Startup Folder File Write
value.author: Roberto Rodriguez (Cyb3rWard0g), OTR (Open Threat Research)
value.description: A General detection for files being created in the Windows startup directory. This could be an indicator of persistence.

value.title: Load Of RstrtMgr.DLL By An Uncommon Process
value.author: Luc Génaux
value.description:
Detects the load of RstrtMgr DLL (Restart Manager) by an uncommon process.
This library has been used during ransomware campaigns to kill processes that would prevent file encryption by locking them (e.g. Conti ransomware, Cactus ransomware). It has also recently been seen used by the BiBi wiper for Windows.
It could also be used for anti-analysis purposes by shut downing specific processes.

value.title: CurrentVersion Autorun Keys Modification
value.author: Victor Sergeev, Daniil Yugoslavskiy, Gleb Sukhodolskiy, Timur Zinniatullin, oscd.community, Tim Shelton, frack113 (split)
value.description: Detects modification of autostart extensibility point (ASEP) in registry.

value.title: Change PowerShell Policies to an Insecure Level
value.author: frack113
value.description: Detects changing the PowerShell script execution policy to a potentially insecure level using the "-ExecutionPolicy" flag.

value.title: Suspicious Script Execution From Temp Folder
value.author: Florian Roth (Nextron Systems), Max Altgelt (Nextron Systems), Tim Shelton
value.description: Detects a suspicious script executions from temporary folder

value.title: Windows Defender Exclusions Added - PowerShell
value.author: Tim Rauch, Elastic (idea)
value.description: Detects modifications to the Windows Defender configuration settings using PowerShell to add exclusions

value.title: Suspicious Outbound SMTP Connections
value.author: frack113
value.description:
Adversaries may steal data by exfiltrating it over an un-encrypted network protocol other than that of the existing command and control channel.
The data may also be sent to an alternate network location from the main command and control server.

value.title: Scheduled Task Creation Via Schtasks.EXE
value.author: Florian Roth (Nextron Systems)
value.description: Detects the creation of scheduled tasks by user accounts via the "schtasks" utility.

value.title: Powershell Defender Exclusion
value.author: Florian Roth (Nextron Systems)
value.description: Detects requests to exclude files, folders or processes from Antivirus scanning using PowerShell cmdlets

value.title: System File Execution Location Anomaly
value.author: Florian Roth (Nextron Systems), Patrick Bareiss, Anton Kutepov, oscd.community, Nasreddine Bencherchali (Nextron Systems)
value.description: Detects the execution of a Windows system binary that is usually located in the system folder from an uncommon location.

value.title: Suspicious New Instance Of An Office COM Object
value.author: Nasreddine Bencherchali (Nextron Systems)
value.description:
Detects an svchost process spawning an instance of an office application. This happens when the initial word application creates an instance of one of the Office COM objects such as 'Word.Application', 'Excel.Application', etc.
This can be used by malicious actors to create malicious Office documents with macros on the fly. (See vba2clr project in the references)

value.title: Usage Of Web Request Commands And Cmdlets - ScriptBlock
value.author: James Pemberton / @4A616D6573
value.description: Detects the use of various web request commands with commandline tools and Windows PowerShell cmdlets (including aliases) via PowerShell scriptblock logs

value.title: Drops script at startup location
value.author: Joe Security
value.description: Drops script at startup location

value.title: PSScriptPolicyTest Creation By Uncommon Process
value.author: Nasreddine Bencherchali (Nextron Systems)
value.description: Detects the creation of the "PSScriptPolicyTest" PowerShell script by an uncommon process. This file is usually generated by Microsoft Powershell to test against Applocker.

value.title: Creation of an Executable by an Executable
value.author: frack113
value.description: Detects the creation of an executable by another executable

value.title: Files With System Process Name In Unsuspected Locations
value.author: Sander Wiebing, Tim Shelton, Nasreddine Bencherchali (Nextron Systems)
value.description:
Detects the creation of an executable with a system process name in folders other than the system ones (System32, SysWOW64, etc.).
It is highly recommended to perform an initial baseline before using this rule in production.

value.title: Python Initiated Connection
value.author: frack113
value.description: Detects a Python process initiating a network connection. While this often relates to package installation, it can also indicate a potential malicious script communicating with a C&C server.

value.title: Usage Of Web Request Commands And Cmdlets
value.author: James Pemberton / @4A616D6573, Endgame, JHasenbusch, oscd.community, Austin Songer @austinsonger
value.description: Detects the use of various web request commands with commandline tools and Windows PowerShell cmdlets (including aliases) via CommandLine

value.title: Schedule Task Creation From Env Variable Or Potentially Suspicious Path Via Schtasks.EXE
value.author: Florian Roth (Nextron Systems)
value.description: Detects Schtask creations that point to a suspicious folder or an environment variable often used by malware

value.title: Change PowerShell Policies to an Insecure Level - PowerShell
value.author: frack113
value.description: Detects changing the PowerShell script execution policy to a potentially insecure level using the "Set-ExecutionPolicy" cmdlet.

value.title: Script Interpreter Execution From Suspicious Folder
value.author: Florian Roth (Nextron Systems), Nasreddine Bencherchali (Nextron Systems)
value.description: Detects a suspicious script execution in temporary folders or folders accessible by environment variables

value.title: Process Creation Using Sysnative Folder
value.author: Max Altgelt (Nextron Systems)
value.description: Detects process creation events that use the Sysnative folder (common for CobaltStrike spawns)

value.title: Suspicious Binaries and Scripts in Public Folder
value.author: The DFIR Report
value.description: Detects the creation of a file with a suspicious extension in the public folder, which could indicate potential malicious activity.

value.title: Use Short Name Path in Command Line
value.author: frack113, Nasreddine Bencherchali
value.description: Detect use of the Windows 8.3 short name. Which could be used as a method to avoid command-line detection

value.title: Desktop.INI Created by Uncommon Process
value.author: Maxime Thiebaut (@0xThiebaut), Tim Shelton (HAWK.IO)
value.description: Detects unusual processes accessing desktop.ini, which can be leveraged to alter how Explorer displays a folder's content (i.e. renaming files) without changing them on disk.

value.title: Suspicious Process Creation
value.author: Florian Roth
value.description: Detects suspicious process starts on Windows systems based on keywords

value.title: Unsigned DLL Loaded by Windows Utility
value.author: Swachchhanda Shrawan Poudel
value.description:
Detects windows utilities loading an unsigned or untrusted DLL.
Adversaries often abuse those programs to proxy execution of malicious code.

value.title: Modification of IE Registry Settings
value.author: frack113
value.description: Detects modification of the registry settings used for Internet Explorer and other Windows components that use these settings. An attacker can abuse this registry key to add a domain to the trusted sites Zone or insert JavaScript for persistence

value.title: Potential Suspicious PowerShell Keywords
value.author: Florian Roth (Nextron Systems), Perez Diego (@darkquassar), Tuan Le (NCSGroup)
value.description: Detects potentially suspicious keywords that could indicate the use of a PowerShell exploitation framework

value.title: CurrentVersion NT Autorun Keys Modification
value.author: Victor Sergeev, Daniil Yugoslavskiy, Gleb Sukhodolskiy, Timur Zinniatullin, oscd.community, Tim Shelton, frack113 (split)
value.description: Detects modification of autostart extensibility point (ASEP) in registry.

value.title: DNS Query To Remote Access Software Domain From Non-Browser App
value.author: frack113, Connor Martin
value.description:
An adversary may use legitimate desktop support and remote access software, such as Team Viewer, Go2Assist, LogMein, AmmyyAdmin, etc, to establish an interactive command and control channel to target systems within networks.
These services are commonly used as legitimate technical support software, and may be allowed by application control within a target environment.
Remote access tools like VNC, Ammyy, and Teamviewer are used frequently when compared with other legitimate software commonly used by adversaries. (Citation: Symantec Living off the Land)

value.title: Hidden Executable In NTFS Alternate Data Stream
value.author: Florian Roth (Nextron Systems), @0xrawsec
value.description: Detects the creation of an ADS (Alternate Data Stream) that contains an executable by looking at a non-empty Imphash

value.title: Hiding Files with Attrib.exe
value.author: Sami Ruohonen
value.description: Detects usage of attrib.exe to hide files from users.

value.title: File Deletion Via Del
value.author: frack113
value.description:
Detects execution of the builtin "del"/"erase" commands in order to delete files.
Adversaries may delete files left behind by the actions of their intrusion activity.
Malware, tools, or other non-native files dropped or created on a system by an adversary may leave traces to indicate to what was done within a network and how.
Removal of these files can occur during an intrusion, or as part of a post-intrusion process to minimize the adversary's footprint.

value.title: Potentially Suspicious Volume Shadow Copy Vsstrace.dll Load
value.author: frack113
value.description: Detects the image load of VSS DLL by uncommon executables

value.title: Communication To Uncommon Destination Ports
value.author: Florian Roth (Nextron Systems)
value.description: Detects programs that connect to uncommon destination ports

value.title: Read Contents From Stdin Via Cmd.EXE
value.author: frack113, Nasreddine Bencherchali (Nextron Systems)
value.description: Detect the use of "<" to read and potentially execute a file via cmd.exe

value.title: WmiPrvSE Spawned A Process
value.author: Roberto Rodriguez @Cyb3rWard0g
value.description: Detects WmiPrvSE spawning a process

value.title: Suspicious Get-WmiObject
value.author: frack113
value.description: The infrastructure for management data and operations that enables local and remote management of Windows personal computers and servers

value.title: New RUN Key Pointing to Suspicious Folder
value.author: Florian Roth (Nextron Systems), Markus Neis, Sander Wiebing, Swachchhanda Shrawan Poudel (Nextron Systems)
value.description: Detects suspicious new RUN key element pointing to an executable in a suspicious folder

value.title: Suspicious Network Command
value.author: frack113, Christopher Peacock '@securepeacock', SCYTHE '@scythe_io'
value.description: Adversaries may look for details about the network configuration and settings of systems they access or through information discovery of remote systems

value.title: Potential Binary Or Script Dropper Via PowerShell
value.author: frack113, Nasreddine Bencherchali (Nextron Systems)
value.description: Detects PowerShell creating a binary executable or a script file.

value.title: PowerShell Web Download
value.author: Florian Roth (Nextron Systems)
value.description: Detects suspicious ways to download files or content using PowerShell

value.title: Suspicious Execution of Powershell with Base64
value.author: frack113
value.description: Commandline to launch powershell with a base64 payload

value.title: Local Accounts Discovery
value.author: Timur Zinniatullin, Daniil Yugoslavskiy, oscd.community
value.description: Local accounts, System Owner/User discovery using operating systems utilities

value.title: Schedule system process
value.author: Joe Security
value.description: Schedule system process

value.title: Potential Dropper Script Execution Via WScript/CScript
value.author: Margaritis Dimitrios (idea), Florian Roth (Nextron Systems), oscd.community, Nasreddine Bencherchali (Nextron Systems)
value.description: Detects wscript/cscript executions of scripts located in user directories

value.title: Office Macro File Creation
value.author: Nasreddine Bencherchali (Nextron Systems)
value.description: Detects the creation of a new office macro files on the systems

value.title: Disable Windows Defender Functionalities Via Registry Keys
value.author: AlertIQ, Ján Trenčanský, frack113, Nasreddine Bencherchali, Swachchhanda Shrawan Poudel
value.description: Detects when attackers or tools disable Windows Defender functionalities via the Windows registry

value.title: Rundll32 Internet Connection
value.author: Florian Roth (Nextron Systems)
value.description: Detects a rundll32 that communicates with public IP addresses

value.title: Potentially Suspicious Desktop Background Change Via Registry
value.author: Nasreddine Bencherchali (Nextron Systems), Stephen Lincoln @slincoln-aiq (AttackIQ)
value.description:
Detects registry value settings that would replace the user's desktop background.
This is a common technique used by malware to change the desktop background to a ransom note or other image.

value.title: Windows Defender Exclusions Added - Registry
value.author: Christian Burkard (Nextron Systems)
value.description: Detects the Setting of Windows Defender Exclusions

value.title: Potential Mpclient.DLL Sideloading
value.author: Bhabesh Raj
value.description: Detects potential sideloading of "mpclient.dll" by Windows Defender processes ("MpCmdRun" and "NisSrv") from their non-default directory.

value.title: Potential Mpclient.DLL Sideloading Via Defender Binaries
value.author: Bhabesh Raj
value.description: Detects potential sideloading of "mpclient.dll" by Windows Defender processes ("MpCmdRun" and "NisSrv") from their non-default directory.

value.title: Browser Started with Remote Debugging
value.author: pH-T (Nextron Systems), Nasreddine Bencherchali (Nextron Systems)
value.description: Detects browsers starting with the remote debugging flags. Which is a technique often used to perform browser injection attacks

value.title: DNS Query Request By Regsvr32.EXE
value.author: Dmitriy Lifanov, oscd.community
value.description: Detects DNS queries initiated by "Regsvr32.exe"

value.title: MacOS FileGrabber Infostealer
value.author: Jason Phang Vern - Onn (Gen Digital)
value.description: Detects execution of FileGrabber on macOS, which is associated with Amos infostealer campaigns targeting sensitive user files.

value.title: PowerShell Script With File Upload Capabilities
value.author: frack113
value.description: Detects PowerShell scripts leveraging the "Invoke-WebRequest" cmdlet to send data via either "PUT" or "POST" method.

value.title: DarkGate - Autoit3.EXE Execution Parameters
value.author: Micah Babinski
value.description:
Detects execution of the legitimate Autoit3 utility from a suspicious parent process. AutoIt3.exe is used within
the DarkGate infection chain to execute shellcode that performs process injection and connects to the DarkGate
command-and-control server.

value.title: Search for Antivirus process
value.author: Joe Security
value.description: Search for Antivirus process

value.title: Silenttrinity Stager Msbuild Activity
value.author: Kiran kumar s, oscd.community
value.description: Detects a possible remote connections to Silenttrinity c2

value.title: System Information Discovery Using System_Profiler
value.author: Stephen Lincoln `@slincoln_aiq` (AttackIQ)
value.description:
Detects the execution of "system_profiler" with specific "Data Types" that have been seen being used by threat actors and malware. It provides system hardware and software configuration information.
This process is primarily used for system information discovery. However, "system_profiler" can also be used to determine if virtualization software is being run for defense evasion purposes.

value.title: Renamed AutoIt Execution
value.author: Florian Roth (Nextron Systems)
value.description:
Detects the execution of a renamed AutoIt2.exe or AutoIt3.exe.
AutoIt is a scripting language and automation tool for Windows systems. While primarily used for legitimate automation tasks, it can be misused in cyber attacks.
Attackers can leverage AutoIt to create and distribute malware, including keyloggers, spyware, and botnets. A renamed AutoIt executable is particularly suspicious.

value.title: Network Connection Initiated By Regsvr32.EXE
value.author: Dmitriy Lifanov, oscd.community
value.description: Detects a network connection initiated by "Regsvr32.exe"

value.title: Uncommon Child Process Of Conhost.EXE
value.author: omkar72
value.description: Detects uncommon "conhost" child processes. This could be a sign of "conhost" usage as a LOLBIN or potential process injection activity.

value.title: MacOS Scripting Interpreter AppleScript
value.author: Alejandro Ortuno, oscd.community
value.description: Detects execution of AppleScript of the macOS scripting language AppleScript.

value.title: Suspicious File Access to Browser Credential Storage
value.author: frack113, X__Junior (Nextron Systems), Swachchhanda Shrawan Poudel (Nextron Systems), Parth-FourCore
value.description:
Detects file access to browser credential storage paths by non-browser processes, which may indicate credential access attempts.
Adversaries may attempt to access browser credential storage to extract sensitive information such as usernames and passwords or cookies.
This behavior is often commonly observed in credential stealing malware.

value.title: Suspicious Msbuild Execution By Uncommon Parent Process
value.author: frack113
value.description: Detects suspicious execution of 'Msbuild.exe' by a uncommon parent process

value.title: Suspicious PowerShell Get Current User
value.author: frack113
value.description: Detects the use of PowerShell to identify the current logged user.

value.title: Execution Of Script Located In Potentially Suspicious Directory
value.author: Joseliyo Sanchez, @Joseliyo_Jstnk
value.description: Detects executions of scripts located in potentially suspicious locations such as "/tmp" via a shell such as "bash", "sh", etc.

value.title: Suspicious Copy From or To System Directory
value.author: Florian Roth (Nextron Systems), Markus Neis, Tim Shelton (HAWK.IO), Nasreddine Bencherchali (Nextron Systems)
value.description:
Detects a suspicious copy operation that tries to copy a program from system (System32, SysWOW64, WinSxS) directories to another on disk.
Often used to move LOLBINs such as 'certutil' or 'desktopimgdownldr' to a different location with a different name in order to bypass detections based on locations.

value.title: File Deletion Via Del
value.author: frack113
value.description:
Detects execution of the builtin "del"/"erase" commands in order to delete files.
Adversaries may delete files left behind by the actions of their intrusion activity.
Malware, tools, or other non-native files dropped or created on a system by an adversary may leave traces to indicate to what was done within a network and how.
Removal of these files can occur during an intrusion, or as part of a post-intrusion process to minimize the adversary's footprint.

value.title: Potential Product Reconnaissance Via Wmic.EXE
value.author: Nasreddine Bencherchali
value.description: Detects the execution of WMIC in order to get a list of firewall and antivirus products

value.title: Communication To Uncommon Destination Ports
value.author: Florian Roth (Nextron Systems)
value.description: Detects programs that connect to uncommon destination ports

value.title: Non Interactive PowerShell Process Spawned
value.author: Roberto Rodriguez @Cyb3rWard0g (rule), oscd.community (improvements)
value.description: Detects non-interactive PowerShell activity by looking at the "powershell" process with a non-user GUI process such as "explorer.exe" as a parent.

value.title: Potential Raspberry Robin Registry Set Internet Settings ZoneMap
value.author: Swachchhanda Shrawan Poudel
value.description:
Detects registry modifications related to the proxy configuration of the system, potentially associated with the Raspberry Robin malware, as seen in campaigns running in Q1 2024.
Raspberry Robin may alter proxy settings to circumvent security measures, ensuring unhindered connection with Command and Control servers for maintaining control over compromised systems if there are any proxy settings that are blocking connections.

value.title: Rundll32 Internet Connection
value.author: Florian Roth (Nextron Systems)
value.description: Detects a rundll32 that communicates with public IP addresses

value.title: Usage Of Web Request Commands And Cmdlets - ScriptBlock
value.author: James Pemberton / @4A616D6573
value.description: Detects the use of various web request commands with commandline tools and Windows PowerShell cmdlets (including aliases) via PowerShell scriptblock logs

value.title: Load Of RstrtMgr.DLL By An Uncommon Process
value.author: Luc Génaux
value.description:
Detects the load of RstrtMgr DLL (Restart Manager) by an uncommon process.
This library has been used during ransomware campaigns to kill processes that would prevent file encryption by locking them (e.g. Conti ransomware, Cactus ransomware). It has also recently been seen used by the BiBi wiper for Windows.
It could also be used for anti-analysis purposes by shut downing specific processes.

value.title: Uncommon Svchost Parent Process
value.author: Florian Roth (Nextron Systems)
value.description: Detects an uncommon svchost parent process

value.title: Windows Processes Suspicious Parent Directory
value.author: vburov
value.description: Detect suspicious parent processes of well-known Windows processes

value.title: Hardware Model Reconnaissance Via Wmic.EXE
value.author: Florian Roth (Nextron Systems)
value.description: Detects the execution of WMIC with the "csproduct" which is used to obtain information such as hardware models and vendor information

value.title: Usage Of Web Request Commands And Cmdlets
value.author: James Pemberton / @4A616D6573, Endgame, JHasenbusch, oscd.community, Austin Songer @austinsonger
value.description: Detects the use of various web request commands with commandline tools and Windows PowerShell cmdlets (including aliases) via CommandLine

value.title: Whoami Utility Execution
value.author: Florian Roth (Nextron Systems)
value.description: Detects the execution of whoami, which is often used by attackers after exploitation / privilege escalation

value.title: Browser Started with Remote Debugging
value.author: pH-T (Nextron Systems), Nasreddine Bencherchali (Nextron Systems)
value.description: Detects browsers starting with the remote debugging flags. Which is a technique often used to perform browser injection attacks

value.title: PowerShell Script With File Upload Capabilities
value.author: frack113
value.description: Detects PowerShell scripts leveraging the "Invoke-WebRequest" cmdlet to send data via either "PUT" or "POST" method.

value.title: Cmd.EXE Missing Space Characters Execution Anomaly
value.author: Florian Roth (Nextron Systems)
value.description:
Detects Windows command lines that miss a space before or after the /c flag when running a command using the cmd.exe.
This could be a sign of obfuscation of a fat finger problem (typo by the developer).

value.title: Suspicious PowerShell Get Current User
value.author: frack113
value.description: Detects the use of PowerShell to identify the current logged user.

value.title: PowerShell Base64 Encoded Invoke Keyword
value.author: pH-T (Nextron Systems), Harjot Singh, @cyb3rjy0t
value.description: Detects UTF-8 and UTF-16 Base64 encoded powershell 'Invoke-' calls

value.title: Potential Homoglyph Attack Using Lookalike Characters
value.author: Micah Babinski, @micahbabinski
value.description:
Detects the presence of unicode characters which are homoglyphs, or identical in appearance, to ASCII letter characters.
This is used as an obfuscation and masquerading techniques. Only "perfect" homoglyphs are included; these are characters that
are indistinguishable from ASCII characters and thus may make excellent candidates for homoglyph attack characters.

value.title: Potential Homoglyph Attack Using Lookalike Characters in Filename
value.author: Micah Babinski, @micahbabinski
value.description:
Detects the presence of unicode characters which are homoglyphs, or identical in appearance, to ASCII letter characters.
This is used as an obfuscation and masquerading techniques. Only "perfect" homoglyphs are included; these are characters that
are indistinguishable from ASCII characters and thus may make excellent candidates for homoglyph attack characters.

value.title: Suspicious Non-Browser Network Communication With Telegram API
value.author: Nasreddine Bencherchali (Nextron Systems)
value.description: Detects an a non-browser process interacting with the Telegram API which could indicate use of a covert C2

value.title: Suspicious PowerShell Encoded Command Patterns
value.author: Florian Roth (Nextron Systems)
value.description: Detects PowerShell command line patterns in combincation with encoded commands that often appear in malware infection chains

value.title: Suspicious Encoded PowerShell Command Line
value.author: Florian Roth (Nextron Systems), Markus Neis, Jonhnathan Ribeiro, Daniil Yugoslavskiy, Anton Kutepov, oscd.community
value.description: Detects suspicious powershell process starts with base64 encoded commands (e.g. Emotet)

value.title: Telegram Bot API Request
value.author: Florian Roth (Nextron Systems)
value.description: Detects suspicious DNS queries to api.telegram.org used by Telegram Bots of any kind

value.title: Potentially Suspicious DMP/HDMP File Creation
value.author: Nasreddine Bencherchali (Nextron Systems)
value.description: Detects the creation of a file with the ".dmp"/".hdmp" extension by a shell or scripting application such as "cmd", "powershell", etc. Often created by software during a crash. Memory dumps can sometimes contain sensitive information such as credentials. It's best to determine the source of the crash.

value.title: Potential PowerShell Obfuscation Using Alias Cmdlets
value.author: frack113
value.description: Detects Set-Alias or New-Alias cmdlet usage. Which can be use as a mean to obfuscate PowerShell scripts

value.title: PowerShell Download and Execution Cradles
value.author: Florian Roth (Nextron Systems)
value.description: Detects PowerShell download and execution cradles.

value.title: Tamper Windows Defender - ScriptBlockLogging
value.author: frack113, elhoim, Tim Shelton (fps, alias support), Swachchhanda Shrawan Poudel, Nasreddine Bencherchali (Nextron Systems)
value.description: Detects PowerShell scripts attempting to disable scheduled scanning and other parts of Windows Defender ATP or set default actions to allow.

value.title: Suspicious PowerShell WindowStyle Option
value.author: frack113, Tim Shelton (fp AWS)
value.description:
Adversaries may use hidden windows to conceal malicious activity from the plain sight of users.
In some cases, windows that would typically be displayed when an application carries out an operation can be hidden

value.title: Suspicious PowerShell Download - Powershell Script
value.author: Florian Roth (Nextron Systems)
value.description: Detects suspicious PowerShell download command

value.title: Local Accounts Discovery
value.author: Timur Zinniatullin, Daniil Yugoslavskiy, oscd.community
value.description: Local accounts, System Owner/User discovery using operating systems utilities

value.title: Usage Of Web Request Commands And Cmdlets - ScriptBlock
value.author: James Pemberton / @4A616D6573
value.description: Detects the use of various web request commands with commandline tools and Windows PowerShell cmdlets (including aliases) via PowerShell scriptblock logs

value.title: Non Interactive PowerShell Process Spawned
value.author: Roberto Rodriguez @Cyb3rWard0g (rule), oscd.community (improvements)
value.description: Detects non-interactive PowerShell activity by looking at the "powershell" process with a non-user GUI process such as "explorer.exe" as a parent.

value.title: System File Execution Location Anomaly
value.author: Florian Roth (Nextron Systems), Patrick Bareiss, Anton Kutepov, oscd.community, Nasreddine Bencherchali (Nextron Systems)
value.description: Detects the execution of a Windows system binary that is usually located in the system folder from an uncommon location.

value.title: Windows Defender Exclusions Added - PowerShell
value.author: Tim Rauch, Elastic (idea)
value.description: Detects modifications to the Windows Defender configuration settings using PowerShell to add exclusions

value.title: Potential Product Reconnaissance Via Wmic.EXE
value.author: Nasreddine Bencherchali
value.description: Detects the execution of WMIC in order to get a list of firewall and antivirus products

value.title: Change PowerShell Policies to an Insecure Level
value.author: frack113
value.description: Detects changing the PowerShell script execution policy to a potentially insecure level using the "-ExecutionPolicy" flag.

value.title: Powershell Create Scheduled Task
value.author: frack113
value.description: Adversaries may abuse the Windows Task Scheduler to perform task scheduling for initial or recurring execution of malicious code

value.title: Powershell Defender Exclusion
value.author: Florian Roth (Nextron Systems)
value.description: Detects requests to exclude files, folders or processes from Antivirus scanning using PowerShell cmdlets

value.title: Hardware Model Reconnaissance Via Wmic.EXE
value.author: Florian Roth (Nextron Systems)
value.description: Detects the execution of WMIC with the "csproduct" which is used to obtain information such as hardware models and vendor information

value.title: PSScriptPolicyTest Creation By Uncommon Process
value.author: Nasreddine Bencherchali (Nextron Systems)
value.description: Detects the creation of the "PSScriptPolicyTest" PowerShell script by an uncommon process. This file is usually generated by Microsoft Powershell to test against Applocker.

value.title: Suspicious Execution of Powershell with Base64
value.author: frack113
value.description: Commandline to launch powershell with a base64 payload
